DTSTAMP:20251029T020335Z
DTSTART:20251021T184000Z
DTEND:20251021T190000Z
SUMMARY:Resilient by Design: How WCMA's MOSS App is Streamlining a Major Collection Move
DESCRIPTION:Faced with the challenge of relocating 15\,000 collection objects in advance of a new building\, the Williams College Museum of Art (WCMA) needed a location tracking solution that was fast\, reliable\, and easy to use. Working with Concrete Computing and Most Media\, WCMA developed MOSS (Museum Object Scanning System)\, a lightweight web app built to streamline barcode-based inventory and moves\, cutting task time in half while improving accuracy and staff coordination. This session offers a case study in rapid\, resilient tool design—showing how targeted digital interventions can support institutional change\, reduce friction in collaboration with IT departments\, and maintain human-centered workflows at scale.
CATEGORIES:15-MINUTE PRESENTATION
LOCATION:Herzog Building\, 5th Floor - Skyline Room\, Minneapolis\, MN\, USA
SEQUENCE:0
UID:102cc426446d06089b864a5ad2a1bf28
URL:http://mcn2025.sched.com/event/102cc426446d06089b864a5ad2a1bf28
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20251029T020335Z
DTSTART:20251021T191500Z
DTEND:20251021T193500Z
SUMMARY:Exploring Collections in Latent Space: Machine Learning for Visual Drift\, Interpolation\, and Insight
DESCRIPTION:Latent space modeling offers a new way to engage with collections—not as rows in a database\, but as fluid visual systems where relationships between objects can be explored\, interpolated\, and reimagined. This presentation introduces a framework for training unsupervised machine learning models—particularly VAEs and VQGANs—on small\, high-resolution image datasets drawn from scientific and cultural collections. By embedding objects in a continuous visual space\, we gain the ability to generate new representations that exist between known examples\, opening up insights into both natural morphology and aesthetic variation.\n\nThe work began with Hawaiian seed imagery\, training species-specific VAEs that could interpolate within narrowly scoped datasets. These models were deliberately limited in scope—trained without CLIP or text-based embeddings—to focus purely on visual properties: symmetry\, texture\, contour\, noise. This constraint revealed a surprising strength: the models began to surface latent structures in the data that reflected phylogenetic relationships\, collection anomalies\, and in some cases\, artistic potential. In short\, the model didn’t need to “know” what it was looking at to find meaningful continuity.\n\nThe presentation covers both the technical workflow and conceptual implications.\n\nBeyond botany\, the same workflow has been applied to objects from archaeological\, ethnographic\, and artistic collections. When trained on carved forms\, textiles\, or repeated motifs\, latent space models offer an alternative mode of formal analysis—surfacing unexpected connections across geography\, culture\, or time. These connections are not prescriptive\; rather\, they open up curatorial and scholarly questions. Why do two distinct artifacts interpolate so cleanly? Why do others resist? What might a “missing” object in the middle of that transition look like?\n\nFor curators and conservators\, this technique offers a speculative framework for analyzing fragmentary or context-poor materials. For scientists\, it provides a new mode of visual hypothesis testing. And for artists or exhibition designers\, it’s a tool for generative creation and interpretive storytelling.\n\nThis talk is intended for those at the intersection of machine learning\, visual collections\, and public knowledge infrastructure. Attendees will leave with reproducible workflows\, model references\, and a broader perspective on how unsupervised image models can support—and challenge—the ways we interpret material culture and natural history.
CATEGORIES:15-MINUTE PRESENTATION
LOCATION:Barnes Building\, 8th Floor - Garden Terrace Room\, Minneapolis\, MN\, USA
SEQUENCE:0
UID:ae8b94385879e829323845c08a33498c
