DTSTAMP:20251029T020335Z
DTSTART:20251021T191500Z
DTEND:20251021T193500Z
SUMMARY:The Cost of Curiosity: How to Budget for Interpretive Exhibits Before You Have All the Answers
DESCRIPTION:We've all been there: A Director\, Board Member\, or partner turns to you and asks\, “How much would it cost to do something like this?” It’s just a spark of an idea—there’s no plan\, no drawing\, and no clear scope. But somehow\, you need to provide a thoughtful\, ballpark estimate that’s grounded in reality and helps keep momentum moving forward.\n\nThis session unpacks how to build a flexible\, high-level exhibit budget in the early phases of a project—before you know all the details. We’ll walk through a real-world framework for creating a Rough Order of Magnitude (ROM) budget\, drawing on best practices and a dynamic cost calculator that breaks down expenses by type\, phase\, and scale.\n\nTogether\, we’ll discuss:\n\n1. Rules of thumb for estimating exhibit costs on a per-square-foot basis&nbsp\;\n\n2. Differentiating capital vs. operating expenses\n\n3. Understanding hard costs (e.g.\, materials\, fabrication\, AV hardware) vs. soft costs (e.g.\, design\, planning\, media development)&nbsp\;\n\n4. Aligning exhibit phases with architectural design phases to improve predictability&nbsp\;\n\n5. How to use the ROM budget as a decision-making tool\, not a crystal ball\n\nAttendees will gain access to a customizable budgeting worksheet that helps build clarity\, consensus\, and confidence around exhibit planning—even in the early\, messy stages. Whether you’re launching a new visitor center or rethinking a gallery on a shoestring\, this session will help you respond to the question behind the question: “What’s it going to take to make this real?”
CATEGORIES:15-MINUTE PRESENTATION
LOCATION:Herzog Building\, 5th Floor - Skyline Room\, Minneapolis\, MN\, USA
SEQUENCE:0
