BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20251029T020335Z
DTSTART:20251021T201500Z
DTEND:20251021T210000Z
SUMMARY:Empowering Institutional Priorities and Strategic Planning with Data
DESCRIPTION:A good strategy helps a complex organization stay mission-focused and serves as a roadmap for guiding decision-making and resource allocation. Developing measures and targets is an essential part of the strategic process\, but putting them into practice can be challenging without the fundamental data and processes in place to support them. Gone wrong\, this can result in locking in on the wrong things. When done well\, it can fuel an iterative and virtuous cycle of critical thinking\, which can inform prioritization and help build data culture.\n\nThis session\, co-presented by the National Gallery of Art’s Chief Strategy and Planning Officer and its data analytics and audience development teams\, will share the National Gallery's approach to using cross-functional data to illustrate its impact and support strategic metrics at all levels of the organization. We will walk through the evolution of our strategic plan and the iterative process of determining measures and developing dashboards to track these metrics in ways that promote transparency and accountability. Participants will hear tangible examples of how this applies in practice to key areas of any museum\, including visitation\, public and educational programming\, and interpretive resources.\n\nIn addition to building in time for Q&A\, the session presenters will invite members of the audience to give examples of dashboards they have created at their Museums and share use-cases of their application. Our presenters will also ask audience members to name big barriers they’ve run into when designing and deploying dashboards\, and the tips and tricks they’ve found to overcome them. Lastly\, as the strategic plan continues to adapt and evolve\, this presentation encourages discussion on how diverse technology tools and resources can support continuous improvement at an institution.
CATEGORIES:45-MINUTE PRESENTATION
LOCATION:Bazinet Lobby - Cinema\, Minneapolis\, MN\, USA
SEQUENCE:0
UID:4a8eb9303f2f7054095a44c18ac900c3
URL:http://mcn2025.sched.com/event/4a8eb9303f2f7054095a44c18ac900c3
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20251029T020335Z
DTSTART:20251021T201500Z
DTEND:20251021T210000Z
SUMMARY:Simpler\, Lighter\, More Effective: Rethinking Infrastructures for Online Collections
DESCRIPTION:New ideas and approaches are emerging that can help museums build robust and performant online collections.&nbsp\;\n\nDespite years of blood\, sweat and tears\, many of the old challenges remain\, and in some cases\, new complexity has crept in. Extracting information and media from legacy systems\, building data pipelines and image services\, and weaving backend systems into an engaging web platform—these are all opportunities for new thinking and innovation.\n\nMoreover\, building sustainably requires more than technology systems\, it means building internal workflows\, staff expertise and governance—it means building a team. There’s nothing quite like a new website and online collection to bring a museum team together.\n\nFresh from the launch of a new online collection\, the technical group behind the new Menil.org—including internal staff\, agency partners and a museum technology consultant—will lead a discussion detailing common approaches\, challenges and new opportunities for building an online collection in 2025.\n\nIntroduction: What good is an online collection? MCN has a long history as a forum for discussing online collections\; let’s keep pushing the state of the art forward.\n\nCollection data: Extracting data from collections management systems and delivering it to the web is a foundational process for online collections\, and it can still be a challenge. We’ll survey different approaches for data extraction\; we’ll touch on the difficulties posed by legacy collections management systems and their web services\; and we’ll survey the usefulness of APIs vs aggregated data files. With this context in mind\, we’ll detail the Menil’s approach\, which replaced a baroque aggregation of eMuseum APIs with an elegant database export to json.\n\nCollection images: Delivering collection images to the web comes with its own challenges. We’ll discuss legacy DAMS and new cloud-based services\; open-access initiatives\; and the opportunities of images-as-data. At the Menil Collection\, the team reconfigured an existing image pipeline with cloud-based storage and Serverless IIIF.\n\nWeb application integration: We’ll discuss different approaches\, including Incremental harvesting vs bulk ingest\; import into the web CMS vs lightweight data integration\; how to keep in sync\; performance and CDNs. For the Menil\, all collection data was delivered in a single json file\, updated nightly\; the web application converted the json to SQLite for use in the online collection.\n\nValues and approaches: Every architecture shows the values of the teams that built it. (Conway’s Law\, etc.) We’ll talk about different infrastructure choices\, and the teams behind them. At the Menil\, the team prized simplicity\, minimalism\, and modularity\, along with a clear separation of concerns.\n\nOnline collections work is an example of innovating with infrastructure: connecting core systems in new ways that promote resilience—sustainability and efficiency\, and provide for resonance—engaging and thoughtful digital experiences.
CATEGORIES:45-MINUTE PRESENTATION
LOCATION:Herzog Building\, 3rd Floor - McGuire Theater\, Minneapolis\, MN\, USA
SEQUENCE:0
