SUMMARY:Where is the #musetech community online?
DESCRIPTION:Where did the #musetech community and institutions go after Twitter became X? We propose holding a campfire session\, where presenters spend a few minutes discussing why they are holding the session\, then opening up the remaining time for audience discussion/participation. We’ll discuss the background of #musetech on Twitter\, and how some audiences are known to be in specific places now (Digital Humanities community is largely on Bluesky). Then attendees will be invited to put dots up on easel pads for what platforms they are on and whether they are Visitor or Resident according to David O. White Visitor/Resident model of online behavior\, as well as if they do social media for an organization or their personal accounts. We will have a discussion about everyone’s thoughts on whether we should try to recreate the online community that we had in the 2010’s on Twitter\, and where are institutions going in the post X era? Where do institutions collaborate? Larger metropolitan areas tend to have professional networks where social media managers can collaborate\, do managers from less populated areas have similar networks? If not\, where do they go? While hashtag campaigns used to go well on Twitter\, what’s working now?\n\nThis session is part 2 of a 3 step endeavor: Step one: We plan to send a survey out to social media managers and other #musetech professionals to get a wide variety of organizations and professionals involved. Step two: hold the campfire session. Step three: publish results of the survey and session in a venue that will be useful to the #musetech community.
CATEGORIES:45-MINUTE PRESENTATION
LOCATION:Barnes Building\, 8th Floor - Garden Terrace Room\, Minneapolis\, MN\, USA
SEQUENCE:0
UID:8678ad9c57e38c4bcb9a1c4bade0e7a5
URL:http://mcn2025.sched.com/event/8678ad9c57e38c4bcb9a1c4bade0e7a5
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20251029T020335Z
DTSTART:20251021T204000Z
DTEND:20251021T210000Z
SUMMARY:Moving Through the Layers: Creating an Immersive Conservation Experience
DESCRIPTION:The conservation of Pintoricchio’s&nbsp\;Virgin and Child offered a rare opportunity to visualize a complex conservation process through digital storytelling. How could we create an experience where visitors move through each layer of conservation\, almost as the conservator had? This question led to Pintoricchio Magnified\, a first-of-its-kind immersive conservation experience.\n\nHidden beneath layers of an early 20th-century restoration\, the Virgin and Child painting was revived through meticulous treatment in the Cleveland Museum of Art’s Painting Conservation Lab. To support visitor understanding of the process\, we developed an immersive digital experience in a traditional gallery space of our permanent collection\, where technology is rarely utilized.\n\nLed by the Digital Innovations team in collaboration with the Painting Conservation team\, the experience invites guests to explore the conservation story interactively. As visitors move through the space\, a 10-by-10-foot digital display responds to their movements\, allowing them to amplify and study specific areas of the painting\, as if viewing it through a microscope and toggle between technical and treatment imaging layers\, revealing the process step by step.\n\nRather than relying on touchscreens or fast-paced interaction\, the experience encourages slow looking. Visitors engage at their own pace\, with the system adjusting subtly to their position. This meditative approach supports close observation and a deeper appreciation for the painting’s materials and structure. The system uses computer vision to track movement and adjust content in real time. Its flexible design suggests future applications for responsive experiences across gallery spaces.\n\nThis session will explore the full lifecycle of Pintoricchio Magnified: An Immersive Conservation Experience\, from concept to design to implementation\, sharing insights on:\n\n- Translating technical material into accessible\, public-facing interpretive experiences\n\n- Methods for inclusive engagement across a wide range of audiences\n\n- Expanding collaboration from focused expert groups to broader internal and external partnerships\n\n- Integrating interactive technology within the constraints of traditional spaces\n\n- Surfacing behind-the-scenes content in responsible and engaging ways\n\n- Strategies for demystifying complex topics and highlighting the often-unseen labor of museum professionals\n\n- Using analytics and evaluation to gain insights and inform future projects\n\nThis session invites museum professionals\, technologists\, and storytellers to explore how immersive digital interpretation can deepen public engagement in behind-the-scenes work and support meaningful innovation.
CATEGORIES:15-MINUTE PRESENTATION
LOCATION:Herzog Building\, 5th Floor - Skyline Room\, Minneapolis\, MN\, USA
