SUMMARY:Emerging Tech in Art Museums: Three* Perspectives
DESCRIPTION:Can museums be hubs for innovation and experimentation? In art museums specifically\, where should that innovation be centered: with artists\, with public engagement\, or somewhere in between? This panel will feature speakers from The Met and the Whitney\, and explore three different takes (not “answers”) to those questions. Each presenter will briefly review their museum’s emerging technology strategy\, where their role fits into the larger organization\, and a case study representing their working model. Case studies will explore recent projects with AI\, blockchain\, and virtual worlds. \n\nA panel discussion will follow\, exploring technology in general (what we’re prioritizing\, what we see as next\, etc)\, and wrestling with what role—if any—museums should play in the larger tech landscape. The panel will also include space for audience questions and group discussion.
CATEGORIES:45-MINUTE PRESENTATION
LOCATION:Herzog Building\, 5th Floor - Skyline Room\, Minneapolis\, MN\, USA
SEQUENCE:0
UID:bc3d4bdbfdc5c2c5a916e23929a349b4
URL:http://mcn2025.sched.com/event/bc3d4bdbfdc5c2c5a916e23929a349b4
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTAMP:20251029T020335Z
DTSTART:20251022T141500Z
DTEND:20251022T150000Z
SUMMARY:Immersive Storytelling that Goes Beyond Traditional Interpretation
DESCRIPTION:Interpretation from expert voices holds the keys to meaningful and memorable engagement with an object or exhibition. But are curatorial and education voices always the most "expert" of perspectives? Where might we look to traditional models of museum interpretation to influence non-traditional interpretation experiences?\n\nIn this session\, the presenters will look at models of audio-based interpretation that invite perspectives from beyond an institution's departmental structure.\n\nAt the Museum of Arts and Design in New York\, a team of producers and actors was enlisted to create an "audio drama" to compliment an exhibition of “worldbuilding” work by artist Saya Woolfalk. Each stop of the audio tour furthered the visitor’s sonic immersion in a fictional narrative expanding on to the exhibition’s utopian themes.. Together\, the full tour becomes a comprehensive audio performance that adds an engaging layer of interpretation and invites the visitor to develop a deeper appreciation of the works on view.\n\nMIT List Visual Arts Center invited rapper and MIT professor Lupe Fiasco to create a site-specific rap and field recording project exploring the relationship between rap and MIT's public art collection. Capturing ambient sounds and crafting lyrics in response to each piece\, the project transforms public art into a living sonic experience—where rap and visual art intersect in real time.
CATEGORIES:45-MINUTE PRESENTATION
LOCATION:Herzog Building\, 3rd Floor - McGuire Theater\, Minneapolis\, MN\, USA
SEQUENCE:0
